The death toll in Dnipro will like increase after Russia launched a devastating attack on Saturday, the city's mayor has claimed. At least 29 deaths have been confirmed and another 44 people remain missing.  A 15-year-old girl was among those killed. A total of 74 people were injured in the strike, with a dozen of those in a serious condition in hospital. Dnipro mayor Borys Filatov said there is a "minimal" chance of finding anyone else alive. He told Reuters: "The chances of saving people now are minimal.    JUST IN: Putin publicly snubs Wagner chief as Kremlin engulfed in volatile power struggle   "I think the number of dead will be in the dozens." Ivan Garnuk was in his apartment when the building was hit. He said he felt lucky to have survived. According to the Mirror, Garnuk said: "There are no military facilities here. There is nothing here.    "There is no air defence, there are no military bases here. It just hit civilians, innocent people." President Volodymyr Zelensky also said: “Search and rescue operations and the dismantling of dangerous structural elements continues. "Around the clock. We continue to fight for every life." The attack appeared to have been orchestrated as missiles rained down on Lviv, Vinnytsia, Mykolaiv, Odesa, Dnipro and KhmeInytskyi.  DON'T MISS:Putin to raise conscript age in desperate bid to bolster troop numbers [LIVE]Met Office issues snow warning to London and other regions [FORECAST]Starmer loses it after Kuennsberg brings up broken promises [INTERVIEW]   Kyiv and Kharkiv were also targeted as Russia ended its two-week hiatus by striking Ukraine's power infrastructure and urban centres. General Valeriy Zaluzhny, the Commander-in-Chief of the Ukrainian Armed Forces, claimed Vladimir Putin's troops fired 33 cruise missiles on Saturday. However, 21 of the cruise missiles launched were reportedly shot down. 